{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox person | name = Balachandran Chullikkad | image = Malayalam poet,.JPG | image_caption = Balachandran Chullikkad | birth_name = M. Balachandran | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1957|7|30}} | birth_place = [[North Paravur|Paravoor]], Kerala, India | occupation = Poet, film actor, lyricist, [[screenplay writer]] | spouse = [[Vijayalakshmi (poet)|Vijayalakshmi]] }}
'''Balachandran Chullikkad''' (born 30 July 1957) is a [[Malayalam]] poet, orator, lyricist and film actor.
==Early and personal life== [[File:Balachandran Chullikkad1.jpg|thumb|Balachandran Chullikkad]] Balachandran was born in Paravur, [[Ernakulam]], Kerala, India.<ref name="ബാലചന്ദ്രന് അറുപത്">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mathrubhumi.com/books/special/balachandran-chullikkadu-60/balachandranchullikkadu-60-1.2127355 |title=ബാലചന്ദ്രന് അറുപത് |date=July 30, 2017 |website=Mathrubhumi |access-date=2017-11-19}}</ref> He completed his graduation in English literature from [[Maharaja's College, Ernakulam|Maharajas College]], [[Ernakulam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Manorama Online : Breaking News, Kerala news, latest news, India, Kerala politics, sports, movies, celebrities, lifestyle, E-paper, Photos & Videos|url=http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/malayalamContentView.do?contentId=14615995&programId=1073752204&channelId=-1073750705&BV_ID=@@@&tabId=3|publisher=[[Malayala Manorama]]|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref>
In 2000 he took Buddhism as his religion.<ref>[http://movies.rediff.com/news/2000/jan/24hindu.htm Malayalam poet embraces Buddhism] Rediff – 24 January 2000</ref> He says that this cannot be called a conversion from [[Hinduism]] because he was never a follower of that religion. "I have not converted because I have not been a believer though I was a Hindu. I have now embraced Buddhism, not converted to Buddhism. The problem with Hinduism is that it is a religion of social status and set-ups. Your value in Hinduism depends on the family in which you were born," he says.<ref>George Iype (4 April 2000). [http://www.rediff.com/news/2000/apr/04faith1.htm "Hindu gods never forgive. They only punish"]. [[Rediff.com]]. Retrieved 10 June 2013.</ref>
Chullikkad is married to [[Vijayalakshmi (poet)|Vijayalakshmi]], a known Malayalam poet and they have a son named Appu. He retired from Kerala State Government service on 31 July 2013. He got National Film Award for Best Non-Feature Film Narration / Voice Over for The 18 Elephants – 3 Monologues in 2003
==Career== His collection of poems published are ''Pathinettu Kavithakal, Amaavaasi, Ghazal, Maanasaantharam, Dracula'' etc. A collection of his complete poems, ''Balachandran Chullikkadinte Kavithakal'' (The Poems of Balachandran Chullikkad, 2000) was published by [[DC Books]], [[Kottayam]], Kerala, India. They have also published the book of his memoirs, ''Chidambarasmarana'' (2001).
He has participated in many national literary seminars organised by Central Academy of Letters, India. He was one among the ten members of a cultural delegation of India to Sweden in 1997 invited by Nobel Academy and Swedish Writers Union. He represented Indian poetry in the international bookfair in Gotenborg, Sweden in November 1997.
Chullikkad is also an actor in [[Malayalam film]]s and serials.<ref>{{cite web|title=Balachandran Chullikkad|url=http://www.malayalachalachithram.com/profiles.php?i=257|publisher=www.malayalachalachithram.com|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=The Hindu |title=Friday Review Thiruvananthapuram / TV Serials : Talkies |url=http://www.thehindujobs.com/thehindu/fr/2008/03/28/stories/2008032850220400.htm |date=28 March 2008 |accessdate=8 March 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523114546/http://www.thehindujobs.com/thehindu/fr/2008/03/28/stories/2008032850220400.htm |archivedate=23 May 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> As an actor, he is best known for [[G. Aravindan]]'s ''[[Pokkuveyil]]'' (1981) in which he played a young artist who lives with his father, a radical friend and a music-loving young woman. The film is about how his world collapses when his father dies, the radical friend leaves him and her family takes the woman away to another city.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl2701/stories/19890610160.htm | title = Aravindan's art | accessdate = 10 June 2013 | author = Sashi Kumar | date = 2–15 January 2010 | publisher = ''[[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]]'' }}</ref>
