{{Infobox language family |name=Central West New Guinea |altname= |region=central [[New Guinea]] |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[Trans–New Guinea languages|Trans–New Guinea]] |child1=Awyu–Ok |child2=Momuna–Mek |glotto=none |glottorefname= |map=Central West New Guinea languages.svg |mapcaption=Map: The Central West New Guinea languages {{legend|#FF5E5F|The CWNG families}} {{legend|#7BB5B6|Other Trans–New Guinea families}} {{legend|#D9D9D9|Other Papuan languages}} {{legend|#E09D00|Austronesian languages}} {{legend|white|Uninhabited}} }}
The '''Central West New Guinea''' languages are a group of [[Trans–New Guinea languages|Trans–New Guinea]] families in central New Guinea established by Timothy Usher, though with precedents in earlier studies.
==Languages== The languages are as follows:<ref>https://sites.google.com/site/newguineaworld/families/trans-new-guinea/central-west-new-guinea</ref>
*Awyu–Ok **[[Digul River languages|Digul River]] (Greater Awyu) **[[Awin–Pa–Kamula languages|Awin–Pa–Kamula]] **[[Ok languages|Ok]] *Momuna–Mek (Somahai–Mek) **[[Mek languages|Mek]] **[[Momina–Momuna languages|Momina–Momuna]] (Somahai)
Voorhoeve (1975) noted a connection between Somahai and the Ok and Dumut languages, but did not consider Mek. (See [[Central and South New Guinea languages]].)
The [[Oksapmin language]] is sometimes classified as the nearest relative of Ok. However, it's unclear whether the similarities are due to relationship or to contact between Oksapmin and Mountain Ok.
