{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Madhav Yeshwant Gadkari | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_date = 25 September 1928 | birth_place = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], India | death_date = 1 June 2006 | death_place = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], India | restingplace = | restingplacecoordinates = | othername = | occupation = Journalist | yearsactive = | known for = Journalism | spouse = | domesticpartner = | children = Three daughters and a son | parents = | website = | awards = [[Padma Shri]] }} '''Madhav Yeshwant Gadkari''' (1928–2006) was an Indian journalist and the editor of [[Loksatta]], a popular [[Marathi language|Marathi]] daily published by the [[Indian Express]] Group.<ref name="Veteran journalist Gadkari passes away">{{cite web | url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-veteran-journalist-gadkari-passes-away-1032701 | title=Veteran journalist Gadkari passes away | date=1 June 2006 | accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref> He was also associated with the [[All India Radio]], ''[[Maharashtra Times]]'', ''[[Sakal]]'' and their [[Goa]] edition, ''Gomantak Times''<ref name="Gomantak Times">[[:nl:Gomantak Times|Gomantak Times, 2015]], Retrieved 27 September 2015{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=October 2015}}</ref> during his career.<ref name="Veteran journalist Gadkari passes away" /> The [[Government of India]] awarded him the fourth highest civilian award of [[Padma Shri]] in 1990.<ref name="Padma Awards">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=21 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 |df= }}</ref>
==Biography== Gadkari was born into Marathi Brahmin<ref>{{cite book|title=Afkār Inquiry, Volume 5, Issues 1-5|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=D95VAAAAYAAJ|publisher=Tropvale Limited|year=1988|page=26|quote=The debate was initiated by Marathi daily Loksatta, owned by the Indian Express group. Editor Madhav Gadkari, a Brahmin condemned the government and accused Ambedkar, a convert to Buddhism, of vilifying Hindu gods and goddesses}}</ref> on 25 September 1928 in Mumbai, in the Western Indian state of [[Maharashtra]].<ref name="Autographs of Media Personalities of India">{{cite web | url=http://www.indianautographs.com/productdetail-131111.html | title=Autographs of Media Personalities of India | publisher=Indian Autographs | date=2015 | accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref> His first known posting was with the [[All India Radio]].<ref name="Veteran journalist Gadkari passes away" /> Later, he worked with ''[[Maharashtra Times]]'', and moved on to [[Sakal]] and their [[Goa]]n edition, Gomantak Times. Subsequently, he joined [[Loksatta]] and became its Group Editor in 1991. After his retirement from service in 1992, he continued freelance writing and contributed a column in the city based newspaper, ''Mumbai Chaufer'', till 1997.<ref name="Veteran journalist Gadkari passes away" />
Gadkari was in the news on more than one occasion. On 20 December 1990, a bomb blast took place in his house following which a few [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] and [[Vishwa Hindu Parishad]] supporters were arrested.<ref name="Altekar gets justice after 16 long years">{{cite web | url=http://www.hindunet.org/hvk/articles/1206/172.html | title=Altekar gets justice after 16 long years | publisher=Hindu Net | date=18 December 2006 | accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref> In 2004, he was again in the news when a group of known personalities including [[Subhash Bhende]], [[Sadashiv Amrapurkar]] and himself, filed a public interest litigation at the [[Mumbai High Court]], seeking [[disenfranchisement]] of the Mumbai slum dwellers.<ref name="Banning the majority from voting">{{cite web | url=http://infochangeindia.org/governance/analysis/banning-the-majority-from-voting.html | title=Banning the majority from voting | publisher=Info Change India | date=October 2004 | accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref> He was awarded the civilian honour of the [[Padma Shri]] by the Government of India in 1990.<ref name="Padma Awards" />
Gadkari died on 1 June 2006, aged 78, at his Mumbai residence, leaving behind his wife, three daughters and a son.<ref name="Veteran journalist Gadkari passes away" />
